data.name: label11.Text
data.value: A stock, also known as a share or equity, represents ownership in a company. When a company goes public and issues shares of stock, individuals and institutions can buy those shares, becoming shareholders in the company. As a shareholder, you have a right to a portion of the company's assets and earnings, as well as voting rights on important company decisions. The price of a stock can fluctuate based on a variety of factors, such as the company's financial performance, industry trends, and overall market conditions.

data.name: label16.Text
data.value: A stock portfolio is a collection of stocks owned by an individual or an entity, such as a mutual fund or an exchange-traded fund (ETF). A stock portfolio is typically created for the purpose of achieving a particular investment objective, such as long-term capital appreciation, regular income, or a balance of both.
